  <section id="design">
    <h2>Platform &amp; Build Quality</h2>
    <p>We did not install or interact with MineeMe directly, so the following is based on vendor descriptions, sales page materials, and social media demo footage referenced in the research brief.</p>

    <h3>Chrome Extension Format</h3>
    <p>MineeMe is distributed as a Chrome browser extension, which means it runs locally in the user's browser rather than as a cloud-based SaaS product. This architecture has practical implications: it requires Chrome to be open and running on a machine where the extension is active. It does not run autonomously in the background on a server, meaning engagement pauses if Chrome is closed. The vendor describes a three-step setup — install, connect, start — marketed as completable in approximately three minutes with no technical skills required.</p>

    <h3>OpenAI API Integration</h3>
    <p>A key design choice that distinguishes MineeMe from simpler comment-spinning tools is the use of the user's own OpenAI API key. This means comment generation is powered by OpenAI's language models directly, rather than a proprietary comment database or template library. It also means OpenAI API usage costs fall to the user separately from the MineeMe subscription — a cost factor the vendor sales page does not prominently address. At typical OpenAI API rates for GPT-4o-mini or similar models, comment generation at light daily volumes would likely represent a modest additional expense, but this depends entirely on usage volume and the model selected.</p>

    <Callout type="info">
      <strong>Cost note:</strong> No ChatGPT Plus subscription is required — only a standard OpenAI API key. API usage is billed separately by OpenAI based on tokens consumed. For light daily engagement at $27/month for MineeMe, total monthly cost may exceed the subscription price depending on comment volume and chosen AI model. Verify current OpenAI API pricing independently.
    </Callout>

    <h3>Safety Controls and the Facebook Risk Question</h3>
    <p>The vendor prominently addresses Facebook safety concerns in the sales copy, describing warm-up and cool-down cycles, natural pause patterns, and behavior that "mimics real human behaviour." The marketing explicitly states it is "not a bot… not a spammer… not random actions… not a risky automation." These are vendor assurances. Facebook's Terms of Service prohibit automated activity on the platform, including automated likes, follows, and comments generated by software rather than human action. Whether warm-up/cool-down pacing is sufficient to avoid detection, or how Facebook's systems would classify AI-generated comments at scale, cannot be confirmed from any independent public source. All safety assurances come solely from the vendor.</p>

    <h3>GPT TOOLS 2 U Ecosystem Placement</h3>
    <p>MineeMe is listed on the GPT TOOLS 2 U product hub alongside other OLSP-affiliated tools including Leads Miner. The product hub frames MineeMe as part of a suite "for regular people" who want to generate commissions online, positioning it as an engagement support tool rather than a standalone business system. The independent OLSP upgrade guidance article explicitly categorizes MineeMe at $27/month as an optional add-on with the note to "pick one" between it and Leads Miner based on individual workflow priorities.</p>
  </section>

