    <h3>Comment Generation Mechanics</h3>
    <p>Once active, MineeMe uses the user's OpenAI API key to generate comments on Facebook posts appearing in the user's feed or defined targets. Comments are described as 2–4 lines and shaped by the user's custom prompts, tone settings, and style preferences — the intent being that output reads like the user wrote it rather than a generic template. The warm-up and cool-down cycles regulate the pace of actions, with the vendor claiming this keeps activity within patterns that resemble organic human behavior. The user can pause, resume, and adjust prompts at any time.</p>

    <h3>Reach and Visibility Claims</h3>
    <p>Vendor marketing states that MineeMe users will see "more reach on every post," "more profile visits," "more algorithm love," and "more warm conversations." These claims are based on the premise that Facebook's algorithm rewards accounts that engage consistently and daily, and that MineeMe maintains that signal even during offline periods. These are <strong>vendor claims</strong>. Facebook's algorithm behavior is not publicly documented in sufficient detail to confirm or deny these specific outcomes, and no independent study of MineeMe's actual effect on organic reach has been published.</p>

    <h3>Independent Reviewer Report (Lead-Gen Platform Version)</h3>
    <p>A publicly available PDF review describes a version of MineeMe as an AI-driven lead generation and outreach platform with dynamic data mining, verified contact information, smart segmentation, and personalized automated follow-ups. That reviewer reported campaign setup time dropping from approximately six hours to under one hour, and cited outreach open rates of 71% and reply rates of 21% in a local business context. These figures are self-reported by a single reviewer and could not be independently verified. Additionally, the lead-generation platform described in that review may refer to a broader or different version of MineeMe rather than the Facebook Chrome extension sold via OLSP — the research brief notes this ambiguity explicitly.</p>

    <Callout type="warn">
      <strong>Account risk warning:</strong> Facebook's Terms of Service prohibit automated engagement generated by software. No independent technical audit of MineeMe's safety controls exists in any public source — all safety assurances come from the vendor. The risk of account restriction, reduced reach, or suspension from automated engagement cannot be assessed independently and should be treated as a real, unquantified risk before subscribing.
    </Callout>
