  <section id="ux">
    <h2>User Experience</h2>

    <h3>Setup Process</h3>
    <p>According to vendor descriptions and social media demo footage, setup involves three steps: install the MineeMe Chrome extension, connect it to a Facebook account and an OpenAI API key, then click "Start Engagement." The vendor markets this as a three-minute process requiring no technical skills. An OpenAI API key requires creating a free OpenAI account and adding billing information — a step not highlighted in the primary vendor copy but necessary before the extension can generate comments. Users without an existing OpenAI account should factor in this preliminary setup.</p>

    <h3>Daily Usage</h3>
    <p>Once running, MineeMe operates within the Chrome browser, generating comments and reactions on Facebook content as the user's browser session progresses. Because it is a browser extension rather than a server-side tool, it requires an active Chrome session to function — it does not run autonomously on a server while the computer is off. Users adjust prompts, pause the tool, or modify tone settings through the extension's interface. The vendor positions the ongoing experience as largely passive: set the parameters, start the extension, and let it maintain the engagement cadence.</p>

    <h3>Customization and Control</h3>
    <p>Custom prompt templates allow users to define what the AI should sound like — formal, casual, enthusiastic, question-asking, value-adding — and adjust these over time as their promotional goals shift. The one-click pause and resume give users control over when the tool runs, which is relevant for managing activity around sensitive periods or when the user wants to engage manually. Training content included with purchase walks through this configuration, though the content itself is gated and cannot be assessed pre-purchase.</p>

    <h3>Learning Curve</h3>
    <p>Setting up an OpenAI API key and understanding how to write effective prompts may require a short learning investment for users with no prior experience with AI APIs. For the intended audience of active Facebook marketers, this is unlikely to be a significant barrier. The bigger learning investment is in calibrating prompts to produce comments that genuinely sound like the user's voice rather than generic AI output — a quality control task that requires ongoing attention rather than a one-time setup.</p>
  </section>

